One Star 
4 x 6 inches
124 pages
Edition of 200

$20 usd + shipping 
Link in bio

There is a massive, nearly perfect sphere of hot plasma, 4.6 billion years old and just far enough away to make life on earth possible. It has been our god, defined our conception of time, and will eventually render our home planet uninhabitable. Meanwhile, here on earth, people experience frustration, disappointment, sadness, and depression—the reasons for which may be as varied as the people on the planet. Or maybe there’s a single, overarching reason; we expect the impossible. Maybe the reason is chemical or cultural. Maybe it’s capitalism. Maybe it’s Maybelline. One cause there seems to be modest agreement on is the sun. More specifically, it’s absence in some regions during certain seasons. The further you go from the earth’s equator, the less consistent the sunlight gets. In northern and southern latitudes, lack of sun in the winter has led to what’s been termed Seasonal Affective Disorder or “SAD”. In response, light therapy products or “SAD lamps” have been developed to help people get through the darker months with a brighter spirit. This book combines one-star reviews of “SAD lamps” with stock photography of our sun—the one star keeping us all alive.

The Knight’s Guy

poster, 16 x 23 inches
Edition of 100

Link in bio

The Knight’s Guy is a collection of pictures of sand, captured exactly as it fell on the glass of a flatbed scanner, and printed at actual scale. Each of the eight images shows a unique sand from a different beach or desert on earth. Here, they’re collated into a 16-page booklet, which is accompanied by a poster exploring some of the ideas implicit in the project.

One Star / Zak Jensen 
Available at www.draw-down.com        
       
An artist book by American designer Zak Jensen, One Star uses found material to construct a striking portrait of consumer concerns and mental health in the twenty-first century. One Star presents a collection of one-star reviews of season affective disorder lamps (SAD lamps) juxtaposed with stock photography of our sun—the one star keeping us all alive. 
 
Designed and published by #ZakJensen, 2023 
Printed in a limited edition of 200 copies

One thing I love about the kind of photographs you find in dictionaries and how-to books is the way they reeeeally try to show us just one thing but almost always show us more. This image, for example, has a lot going on. I think it was from some kind of home maintenance book. I question the inclusion of the wedding ring, but am more fascinated by the watch, which almost seems to have been pushed up on the wrist in order to fit inside the photo. If this was a film, I might wonder if the watch was a plot device like a MacGuffin that’s been conspicuously shown here for us to remember later on.
